{"cursor":"14166","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox Officeholder |name = Rupiah Banda |image = Rupiah Banda.jpg |office =\n4th President of Zambia |vicepresident = George Kunda |term_start = 29 June 2008\n|term_end = 23 September 2011 Acting: 29 June 2008 â 2 November\n2008 |predecessor = Levy Mwanawasa |successor = Michael Sata |office2 =\nVice President of Zambia |president2 = Levy Mwanawasa |term_start2 = 9 October\n2006 |term_end2 = 2 November 2008 |predecessor2 = Lupando Mwape |successor2 =\nGeorge Kunda |birth_name=Rupiah Bwezani Banda |birth_date = |birth_place =\nGwanda, Southern Rhodesia (now Zimbabwe) |death_date =\n|death_place = |party = MMD |spouse = Hope Mwansa Makulu\n(Deceased) Thandiwe Banda |children = 7 |alma_mater = Addis\nAbaba University Lund University Wolfson College, Cambridge |religion =\nAnglicanism [http://www.banda4zambia.com/press/news/viewnews.cgi?category=5-\n&id=1225092565 ] }} 'Rupiah Bwezani Banda' (born 13 February 1937) is a\nZambian politician who was President of Zambia from 2008 to 2011.\n\nDuring the Presidency of Kenneth Kaunda, Banda held important diplomatic posts\nand was active in politics as a member of the United National Independence Party\n(UNIP). Years later, he was appointed as Vice-President by President Levy\nMwanawasa in October 2006, following the latter's re-election. Shapi Shacinda, [http://www.int.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_i-\nd=68&art_id=qw1160400961250B251 \"Mwanawasa warns challenger, names new\ncabinet\"], Reuters (IOL), October 9, 2006. He took over Mwanawasa's\npresidential responsibilities after Mwanawasa suffered a stroke in June\n2008, James Butty, [http://voanews.com/english/archive/2008-07/2008-07-01-\nvoa8.cfm?CFID=61434207&CFTOKEN=25482061 \"Zambian President Has Had a History of\nHypertension, Says Information Minister\"], VOA News, July 2, 2008. and\nfollowing Mwanawasa's death in August 2008, he became acting President. As the\ncandidate of the governing Movement for Multiparty Democracy (MMD), he narrowly\nwon the October 2008 presidential election, according to official results. [http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=84&art_id=nw200811-\n02170239312C293933 \"Zambia: Banda sworn in, riots spread\"], Sapa-DPA (IOL),\nNovember 2, 2008.\n\nOpposition leader Michael Sata defeated Banda in the September 2011 presidential\nelection, and Sata accordingly succeeded Banda as President on 23 September\n2011. [http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/world/2011-\n09/23/c_131155939.htm Sata wins Zambia 2011 presidential election]\n","linknr":311,"url":"Rupiah_Banda","recorded":1375082228,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Rupiah_Banda&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Rupiah_Banda&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/File:Rupiah_Banda.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7c/Rupiah_Banda.jpg/220px-Rupiah_Banda.jpg","/wiki/President_of_Zambia","/wiki/Acting_(law)","/wiki/George_Kunda","/wiki/Levy_Mwanawasa","/wiki/Michael_Sata","/wiki/Vice_President_of_Zambia","/wiki/Levy_Mwanawasa","/wiki/Lupando_Mwape","/wiki/George_Kunda","/wiki/Gwanda","/wiki/Southern_Rhodesia","/wiki/Zimbabwe","/wiki/Movement_for_Multi-Party_Democracy","/wiki/Alma_